How do these ideas relate to the war in Peru? The Peruvian war was fought mainly in the remoter parts of Ayacucho and the central Andes, where the transport and communication infrastructure was generally very poor and population density was very low (Ball et al., 2003). It is likely that the provision of security and services for villagers would require a logistic effort too costly ever to be a credible strategy for either the government or SL. Protecting a remote village would require a continual presence there; intimidation could be achieved by an occasional visit. Another factor lowering the cost of intimidation relative to protection was the fact that many victims were members of an ethnic minority with whom the urban electorate did not identify. More violence by one side is therefore likely to be associated with more violence by the other. Despite the disparity in the size of each belligerent (government forces numbering around 100,000 troops and insurgent forces numbering less than 10,000), the physical geography of Peru is likely to have created a strategic symmetry. For this reason, the marked strategic asymmetries seen in cycles of violence in some other countries (for example those in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict documented by Jaeger & Paserman, 2008

4
) may not appear in Peru.

